{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474696"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:23:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:23:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12293"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12293"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.11,0.61,0.16,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4815"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46499"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4815"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12293"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31410"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"5872"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7727"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7729"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44120"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46499"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 6-year-old schoolboy is brought to the clinic by his mother, who is concerned about episodes of blank stares he had over the last month. He has these \u0027spells\u0027 some 10-20 times a day and each one lasts for around 30 seconds, during which time he is unresponsive. During the spell, the child loses awareness, stops his activity completely and starts staring blankly into space. On physical examination, the doctor is able to trigger such an episode by asking the child to blow repetitively for two minutes. An electroencephalogram with video telemetry shows bilaterally synchronous and symmetrical 3-Hertz spike-and-wave discharges that start and end abruptly.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lamotrigine","Valproic acid","Ethosuximide","Levetiracetam","Zonisamide"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe child has presented with \u0022absence seizures\u0022, brief and multiple \u0022spells\u0022 of blank staring associated with unresponsiveness, loss of awareness and activity that are triggered by hyperventilation. They are manifest as bilaterally synchronous and symmetrical 3-Hertz spike-and-wave discharges are all characteristics of absence seizures. The best medication used for the treatment of absence seizures in children more than three years of age is \u003Cstrong\u003Eethosuximide,\u003C/strong\u003E which is an antiepileptic drug specifically used for this purpose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELamotrigine\u003C/strong\u003E can be used for the management of absence seizures but it is less effective as compared to ethosuximide and according to a study is associated with around half the amount of people becoming seizure-free after taking it as compared to people taking ethosuximide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EValproic acid \u003C/strong\u003Eis used for the treatment of absence seizures but ethosuximide is usually preferred because of the lower risk of side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELevetiracetam\u003C/strong\u003E is a second-line management option for absence seizures and can be used as an adjunctive therapy but it is not preferred over ethosuximide as a first-line therapy because of its lower efficacy as compared to ethosuximide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZonisamide\u003C/strong\u003E is also a second-line management option for absence seizures that can be used as an adjunct therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ethosuximide is the best drug for the treatment of absence seizures."],"references":["Albuja AC, Khan GQ. Absence Seizure. [Updated 2022 Oct 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.","Brigo F, Igwe SC. Ethosuximide, sodium valproate or lamotrigine for absence seizures in children and adolescents. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2017 Feb 14;2(2)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31410"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12293"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31410"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-05T17:49:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-05T17:49:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4815"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46499"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGro